On Tue, Jan 10, 2012 at 03:19, Markus Lanthaler
&lt;markus.lanthaler@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; does your opinion hold the same:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; - when the target resources are not binary as in the example you
&gt;&gt; supplied, but are instead text?
&gt;
&gt; Yes, that doesn&#39;t matter from the client&#39;s POV. It either has the required
&gt; codec to interpret the representation or not. According to you, what should
&gt; that change?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt; - when there are multiple transclusion links in the same
&gt;&gt; representation?
&gt;
&gt; Yes
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt; - when the client&#39;s goal is to compare several resources and produce
&gt;&gt; output?
&gt;
&gt; Yes, because in both cases it has to dereference the resources and compare
&gt; the retrieved representations.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;&gt; - when the client&#39;s goal is to combine several resources and store the
&gt;&gt; result?
&gt;
&gt; This one might be a bit trickier because if you would really have LE which
&gt; is not dependent on a specific MIME-type you could generalize your client to
&gt; do just that task. But as far as I know, such a MIME type independent LE
&gt; doesn&#39;t exist and so again it is up to the client to understand the
&gt; semantics associated to that specific element in that specific MIME type to
&gt; proceed.
&gt; In HTML the LE as e.g. used in the &lt;img&gt; tag is necessary because the client
&gt; (browser) has a hardcoded knowledge of what an &lt;img&gt; is and how it should be
&gt; rendered.
&gt; Looking at the favicon it is not that clear weather that&#39;s LE or LO - or is
&gt; it? It would as well been possible to reuse the &lt;img&gt; tag in the header for
&gt; this. Instead a generic &lt;link&gt; was used and the information on how to
&gt; process it was moved into the &quot;rel&quot; attribute. Why was it done that way? IMO
&gt; to introduce without needing to change the MIME type, i.e., HTML in this
&gt; case. So the semantics in this case are out-of-band and not defined in the
&gt; MIME type and yet it works quite well in practice.
